If I could have given a lower rating I would have. From the time we entered until the time we left, the experience was a HUGE disappointment.  Our family is pescatarian, so we ordered vegetarian friendly options. After placing our orders, including two vegetable burritos, we were told there was no guacamole, which is offered as a substitute when no meat is chosen.  Meanwhile, while wrapping my burrito, the shell broke. The burrito maker asked for another one. Upon being given one, she wrapped the remaining items from my burrito that didn’t fall on the counter or floor—all of which amounted to approximately half a burrito.  I asked for her to add some more rice,When beans, and add-ons to make a full burrito, I was told that was not an option. (So now, we’re down half a burrito and we have no guacamole).  As the burrito was being rewrapped, the worker’s hair band fell down around her hand. Not only unsanitary, but no attempt to acknowledge or address the issue.  We ordered fountain beverages for the adults. Kids also selected fountain drinks because they didn’t want milk or juice. Paid for our order. Went to get beverages from the soda machine—no sodas available and no carbonation. Went to address the non-functioning machine with the cashier whom we had just paid. She acknowledged that she knew it was broken but suggested we just use the water or drink the iced tea. When I asked for her to give us a credit or exchange for other beverages, she said she was only able to offer an exchange for the children’s beverages. “As adults you can just drink water or tea,” was what one of the men behind the counter said.  Thankfully, while at the counter, I checked my bill and happened to see that I had been charged for an extra burrito—a steak burrito that I didn’t order and did not receive. Thankfully, the cashier was able to offer a refund for the burrito I neither ordered nor received.  Went to find a table. Not a clean one to be found! Neither inside nor out.  As we ate, we also watched as the friends of staff (or off duty staff) went back and forth into the kitchen area to joke, talk, and show worker’s videos/texts/images on their cellphones. One of these individuals was charging their phone between the soda fountain and iced tea, with him standing in front of the iced tea staring into his screen. This made it impossible to get to the iced tea, without asking the gentleman to move.  Over the years I’ve had a number of Chipotle experiences. Thankfully, every single one has been better than this.
